+ 2 POSITION
POSITIONING THE SCREEN:
 
 
T/Maker can be thought of as a very large chalkboard.
 
We can do large "hops" around our chalkboard by typing in row/column
coordinates at the WHAT NEXT? prompt.
 
Note:  Upper left-hand coordinates are shown left of the WHAT NEXT? prompt.
+ 2 LIST
1/1 WHAT NEXT?  <LIST>
 
 
 
 
LIST will allow you to view a disk file without affecting the working area.
 
 
 
You can use  LIST  when  you  want  to  view two disk files simultaneously.
The LISTing can be stopped and started by hitting any key.
+ 2 MERGE
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <MERGE>
 
 
MERGE will superimpose a disk file on top of the current work space.
+ 2 MIX
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <MIX>
 
 
The MIX command encrypts or "de-crypts" your current working file with  a
given password,  rendering it readable or unreadable.
 
The password  must be two or more characters in length and cannot contain
a slash (/) or blank spaces.
 
 
WARNING : T/Maker's MIX command is FOOLPROOF. If you forget your password,
=======   you can forget your data encrypted file.
 
 
To help you remember your password,  you may give the password a clue.
A clue is separated from the password by a slash (/).
 
 Example:   1/1 WHAT NEXT?  MIX  Rover/DOG
+ 2 RENAME
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <RENAME>
 
 
 
RENAME  will  "rename" the current work space.  In a sense,  you are
CREATE-ing a new file, except that it already has information in it.
 
 
Because  RENAME  effectively  CREATEs a new file, you must SAVE  the
"new" file if you want to keep it.
+ 2 SAVE
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <SAVE>  or  < S >
 
 
SAVE  will copy the entire contents of the work space onto  disk
using the name of the current work file.
 
Upon  each  SAVE,  the  previous  version  will be automatically
renamed  with  the file extension: filename.BAK.
+ 2 STOP
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <STOP>
 
 
STOP exits you from T/Maker and sends you back to the Operating System.
+ 1 BAR
1/1 WHAT NEXT?   <BAR>
 
 
 
BAR prepares a BAR Chart based upon the values in either one column
or one row of a table.  This Table must be in the working file  and
must also conform to the format requirements of the COMPUTE command.
 
 
You can choose how the BAR Chart will be presented by experimenting
with various options.
 
 
BAR Charts may either be displayed, or placed into the working file
for EDITing and PRINTing.
 
 
 
